In Java, the == operator compares the object references, while the `equals()` method compares the values of the objects.

The == operator checks if both operands refer to the same object. It does not compare the values of the objects. For example, if you have two different String objects with the same content, they will not refer to the same object, and comparing them with == will result in `false`.

```java
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "Hello";
System.out.println(str1 == str2); // false
```

In contrast, the `equals()` method is designed to compare the values of objects of classes that implement the `equals()` method. For `String` objects in Java, the `equals()` method compares their content.

```java
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "Hello";
